There are only two ways compliance operates.

Your system runs it.

Or your team does.

## When the System Runs It

- Tasks are created automatically  
- Ownership is assigned by default  
- Execution happens within workflows  
- Evidence is generated during execution  

No one needs to remember.

No one needs to follow up.

The system does not pause.

## When the Team Runs It

- Tasks are tracked manually  
- Ownership is clarified repeatedly  
- Execution depends on reminders  
- Evidence is collected before audits  

Work continues only when pushed.

Consistency depends on effort.

## The Illusion of the Middle

Most teams believe they are in between.

They have:

- A tool  
- Some automation  
- Some structure  

But still rely on:

- Follow-ups  
- Coordination  
- Deadlines  

This is not a middle state.

It is a human-driven system with partial visibility.

## What Decides the Outcome

The deciding factor is simple:

What happens if no one intervenes?

- If work continues, the system runs compliance  
- If work stops, the team does  

## The Constraint

Human-driven systems do not scale.

They increase:

- Coordination overhead  
- Execution gaps  
- Audit risk  

System-driven models stabilize as complexity increases.

## The Reality

There is no stable hybrid.

One will dominate.

And the system will behave accordingly.
